    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, I see what you mean about the broad language. It feels like there's a lot of room for them to catch me off guard. Do you think there are \"hidden\" traps in these types of clauses that aren't immediately obvious? Like, is there a way they can make it seem like I'm responsible for things that aren't even my fault?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A common hidden trap is the \"consequential damages\" exclusion not being mutual; while they might limit their own liability, this clause could require you to cover *all* consequential damages for them. Also, read carefully to see if the indemnification is required even if the breach was only passive, rather than active negligence. Always try to negotiate a mutual indemnity clause to share the risk fairly.",
      "source": "target",
